         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne bot Garden ¶ 3/12/71 ¶  ¶ P|ossibly, dear Mr Bentham, a letter of yours went to the seabottom in the Rangoon. ¶  So I wait with further sendings till next mail. The Orchideae are probably ne...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">71.12.03</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, f. 29.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne bot Garden</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">3/12/71</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>P|ossibly, dear Mr Bentham, a letter of yours went to the seabottom in the Rangoon.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Rangoon </seg>
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>struck a rock while leaving Galle Harbour on 1 November: 'All lives were saved, but the whole of the Australian mails, the cargo and the passengers' baggage were lost' (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">Argus</seg>, 27 November 1871, p. 5).</p>
               </note> So I wait with further sendings till next mail. The <name key="Orchideae">Orchideae</name> are probably next wanted by you, but I have still a large box full of supplemental <name key="Euphorbiaceae">Euphorbiaceae</name> &amp;c, to despatch to you. The Confusion in the Department, mainly caused by one of the present employees of Mess Edw Wilson &amp; MKinnon<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Not identified.</p>
               </note> has thrown my bot. labours much in arrear.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>You will have doubtless seen the precious document of G Reichenbach on <name key="Orchideae">Orchideae</name> of Austr.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Reichenbach (1871). M is reacting to less than favourable comments when some of his work is cited. M responded to Reichenbach (1871) in B71.12.03, pp. 134-5.</p>
               </note> I think, that I first suggested to him to work up RBr's original <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">specimens</hi>
               </seg>, so that we might get an idea what species they represented, which in many cases remained a guess-work. I was even generous enough to send him myself a lot of specimens of Austr <name key="Orchideae">Orchideae</name>, little expecting the snearing ungrateful remarks afterwards made by him. How unworthy to give me the advise to soak up<seg style="font-weight: bold; "> </seg>plants before I describe them, a thing I have done for more than 30 years.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Reichenbach (1871), p. 52, as part of a critical comment on M's analysis <seg style="font-style: italic; ">of Bolbophyllum shepherdii</seg>: <seg style="">'Wir rathen dringend, in Zukunft die Exemplare schön aufzuweichen und zu analysiren.' [</seg>We strongly advise in future to carefully soften and analyse the specimens.]</p>
               </note> After this I <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">distinctly revoke</hi>
               </seg> any concessions of access to my orchideae by G Reichenbach as I do not want them misused. So please, should he apply for duplicates, let them be directly and indirectly be refused. I had <name key="Dracaea">Dracaea</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Drakaea?</p>
               </note> on my table, when his program came, and should have made the union of <name key="Arthrostylis">Arthrostylis</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Arthrochilus?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> &amp; <name key="Spiculaea">Spiculaea</name> myself.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See Reichenbach (1871), p. 68.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> It seems a pity, that one author should unnecessarily encroach on the territory and work of an other one; assuredly the bot. world is wide enough for all. The accumulation of specimens gives of course facilities for solving doubts, which the first describer not had, and that<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Text ends without valediction a little above the bottom of p. 4.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
